const BIBLE = {"1": {"1": "James, a servant of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ,* to the twelve tribes which are in the Dispersion: Greetings.", "2": "Count it all joy, my brothers,† when you fall into various temptations,", "3": "knowing that the testing of your faith produces endurance.", "4": "Let endurance have its perfect work, that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing.", "5": "But if any of you lacks wisdom, let him ask of God, who gives to all liberally and without reproach, and it will be given to him.", "6": "But let him ask in faith, without any doubting, for he who doubts is like a wave of the sea, driven by the wind and tossed.", "7": "For that man shouldn’t think that he will receive anything from the Lord.", "8": "He is a double-minded man, unstable in all his ways.", "9": "Let the brother in humble circumstances glory in his high position;", "10": "and the rich, in that he is made humble, because like the flower in the grass, he will pass away.", "11": "For the sun arises with the scorching wind and withers the grass; and the flower in it falls, and the beauty of its appearance perishes. So the rich man will also fade away in his pursuits.", "12": "Blessed is a person who endures temptation, for when he has been approved, he will receive the crown of life which the Lord promised to those who love him.", "13": "Let no man say when he is tempted, “I am tempted by God,” for God can’t be tempted by evil, and he himself tempts no one.", "14": "But each one is tempted when he is drawn away by his own lust and enticed.", "15": "Then the lust, when it has conceived, bears sin. The sin, when it is full grown, produces death.", "16": "Don’t be deceived, my beloved brothers.", "17": "Every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, with whom can be no variation nor turning shadow.", "18": "Of his own will he gave birth to us by the word of truth, that we should be a kind of first fruits of his creatures.", "19": "So, then, my beloved brothers, let every man be swift to hear, slow to speak, and slow to anger;", "20": "for the anger of man doesn’t produce the righteousness of God.", "21": "Therefore, putting away all filthiness and overflowing of wickedness, receive with humility the implanted word, which is able to save your souls.‡", "22": "But be doers of the word, and not only hearers, deluding your own selves.", "23": "For if anyone is a hearer of the word and not a doer, he is like a man looking at his natural face in a mirror;", "24": "for he sees himself, and goes away, and immediately forgets what kind of man he was.", "25": "But he who looks into the perfect law of freedom and continues, not being a hearer who forgets but a doer of the work, this man will be blessed in what he does.", "26": "If anyone among you thinks himself to be religious while he doesn’t bridle his tongue, but deceives his heart, this man’s religion is worthless.", "27": "Pure religion and undefiled before our God and Father is this: to visit the fatherless and widows in their affliction, and to keep oneself unstained by the world."}, "2": {"1": "My brothers, don’t hold the faith of our glorious Lord Jesus Christ with partiality.", "2": "For if a man with a gold ring, in fine clothing, comes into your synagogue,* and a poor man in filthy clothing also comes in,", "3": "and you pay special attention to him who wears the fine clothing and say, “Sit here in a good place;” and you tell the poor man, “Stand there,” or “Sit by my footstool”", "4": "haven’t you shown partiality among yourselves, and become judges with evil thoughts?", "5": "Listen, my beloved brothers. Didn’t God choose those who are poor in this world to be rich in faith and heirs of the Kingdom which he promised to those who love him?", "6": "But you have dishonored the poor man. Don’t the rich oppress you and personally drag you before the courts?", "7": "Don’t they blaspheme the honorable name by which you are called?", "8": "However, if you fulfill the royal law according to the Scripture, “You shall love your neighbor as yourself,”✡ you do well.", "9": "But if you show partiality, you commit sin, being convicted by the law as transgressors.", "10": "For whoever keeps the whole law, and yet stumbles in one point, he has become guilty of all.", "11": "For he who said, “Do not commit adultery,”✡ also said, “Do not commit murder.”✡ Now if you do not commit adultery but do murder, you have become a transgressor of the law.", "12": "So speak and so do as men who are to be judged by the law of freedom.", "13": "For judgment is without mercy to him who has shown no mercy. Mercy triumphs over judgment.", "14": "What good is it, my brothers, if a man says he has faith, but has no works? Can faith save him?", "15": "And if a brother or sister is naked and in lack of daily food,", "16": "and one of you tells them, “Go in peace. Be warmed and filled;” yet you didn’t give them the things the body needs, what good is it?", "17": "Even so faith, if it has no works, is dead in itself.", "18": "Yes, a man will say, “You have faith, and I have works.” Show me your faith without works, and I will show you my faith by my works.", "19": "You believe that God is one. You do well. The demons also believe—and shudder.", "20": "But do you want to know, vain man, that faith apart from works is dead?", "21": "Wasn’t Abraham our father justified by works, in that he offered up Isaac his son on the altar?", "22": "You see that faith worked with his works, and by works faith was perfected.", "23": "So the Scripture was fulfilled which says, “Abraham believed God, and it was accounted to him as righteousness,”✡ and he was called the friend of God.", "24": "You see then that by works a man is justified, and not only by faith.", "25": "In the same way, wasn’t Rahab the prostitute also justified by works when she received the messengers and sent them out another way?", "26": "For as the body apart from the spirit is dead, even so faith apart from works is dead."}, "3": {"1": "Let not many of you be teachers, my brothers, knowing that we will receive heavier judgment.", "2": "For we all stumble in many things. Anyone who doesn’t stumble in word is a perfect person, able to bridle the whole body also.", "3": "Indeed, we put bits into the horses’ mouths so that they may obey us, and we guide their whole body.", "4": "Behold,* the ships also, though they are so big and are driven by fierce winds, are yet guided by a very small rudder, wherever the pilot desires.", "5": "So the tongue is also a little member, and boasts great things. See how a small fire can spread to a large forest!", "6": "And the tongue is a fire. The world of iniquity among our members is the tongue, which defiles the whole body, and sets on fire the course of nature, and is set on fire by Gehenna.†", "7": "For every kind of animal, bird, creeping thing, and sea creature is tamed, and has been tamed by mankind;", "8": "but nobody can tame the tongue. It is a restless evil, full of deadly poison.", "9": "With it we bless our God and Father, and with it we curse men who are made in the image of God.", "10": "Out of the same mouth comes blessing and cursing. My brothers, these things ought not to be so.", "11": "Does a spring send out from the same opening fresh and bitter water?", "12": "Can a fig tree, my brothers, yield olives, or a vine figs? Thus no spring yields both salt water and fresh water.", "13": "Who is wise and understanding among you? Let him show by his good conduct that his deeds are done in gentleness of wisdom.", "14": "But if you have bitter jealousy and selfish ambition in your heart, don’t boast and don’t lie against the truth.", "15": "This wisdom is not that which comes down from above, but is earthly, sensual, and demonic.", "16": "For where jealousy and selfish ambition are, there is confusion and every evil deed.", "17": "But the wisdom that is from above is first pure, then peaceful, gentle, reasonable, full of mercy and good fruits, without partiality, and without hypocrisy.", "18": "Now the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace by those who make peace."}, "4": {"1": "Where do wars and fightings among you come from? Don’t they come from your pleasures that war in your members?", "2": "You lust, and don’t have. You murder and covet, and can’t obtain. You fight and make war. You don’t have, because you don’t ask.", "3": "You ask, and don’t receive, because you ask with wrong motives, so that you may spend it on your pleasures.", "4": "You adulterers and adulteresses, don’t you know that friendship with the world is hostility toward God? Whoever therefore wants to be a friend of the world makes himself an enemy of God.", "5": "Or do you think that the Scripture says in vain, “The Spirit who lives in us yearns jealously”?", "6": "But he gives more grace. Therefore it says, “God resists the proud, but gives grace to the humble.”✡", "7": "Be subject therefore to God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you.", "8": "Draw near to God, and he will draw near to you. Cleanse your hands, you sinners. Purify your hearts, you double-minded.", "9": "Lament, mourn, and weep. Let your laughter be turned to mourning and your joy to gloom.", "10": "Humble yourselves in the sight of the Lord, and he will exalt you.", "11": "Don’t speak against one another, brothers. He who speaks against a brother and judges his brother, speaks against the law and judges the law. But if you judge the law, you are not a doer of the law but a judge.", "12": "Only one is the lawgiver, who is able to save and to destroy. But who are you to judge another?", "13": "Come now, you who say, “Today or tomorrow let’s go into this city and spend a year there, trade, and make a profit.”", "14": "Yet you don’t know what your life will be like tomorrow. For what is your life? For you are a vapor that appears for a little time and then vanishes away.", "15": "For you ought to say, “If the Lord wills, we will both live, and do this or that.”", "16": "But now you glory in your boasting. All such boasting is evil.", "17": "To him therefore who knows to do good and doesn’t do it, to him it is sin."}, "5": {"1": "Come now, you rich, weep and howl for your miseries that are coming on you.", "2": "Your riches are corrupted and your garments are moth-eaten.", "3": "Your gold and your silver are corroded, and their corrosion will be for a testimony against you and will eat your flesh like fire. You have laid up your treasure in the last days.", "4": "Behold, the wages of the laborers who mowed your fields, which you have kept back by fraud, cry out; and the cries of those who reaped have entered into the ears of the Lord of Armies.*", "5": "You have lived in luxury on the earth, and taken your pleasure. You have nourished your hearts as in a day of slaughter.", "6": "You have condemned and you have murdered the righteous one. He doesn’t resist you.", "7": "Be patient therefore, brothers, until the coming of the Lord. Behold, the farmer waits for the precious fruit of the earth, being patient over it, until it receives the early and late rain.", "8": "You also be patient. Establish your hearts, for the coming of the Lord is at hand.", "9": "Don’t grumble, brothers, against one another, so that you won’t be judged. Behold, the judge stands at the door.", "10": "Take, brothers, for an example of suffering and of perseverance, the prophets who spoke in the name of the Lord.", "11": "Behold, we call them blessed who endured. You have heard of the perseverance of Job and have seen the Lord in the outcome, and how the Lord is full of compassion and mercy.", "12": "But above all things, my brothers, don’t swear—not by heaven, or by the earth, or by any other oath; but let your “yes” be “yes”, and your “no”, “no”, so that you don’t fall into hypocrisy.†", "13": "Is any among you suffering? Let him pray. Is any cheerful? Let him sing praises.", "14": "Is any among you sick? Let him call for the elders of the assembly, and let them pray over him, anointing him with oil in the name of the Lord;", "15": "and the prayer of faith will heal him who is sick, and the Lord will raise him up. If he has committed sins, he will be forgiven.", "16": "Confess your sins to one another and pray for one another, that you may be healed. The insistent prayer of a righteous person is powerfully effective.", "17": "Elijah was a man with a nature like ours, and he prayed earnestly that it might not rain, and it didn’t rain on the earth for three years and six months.", "18": "He prayed again, and the sky gave rain, and the earth produced its fruit.", "19": "Brothers, if any among you wanders from the truth and someone turns him back,", "20": "let him know that he who turns a sinner from the error of his way will save a soul from death and will cover a multitude of sins."}};
const RW = {"kw": [{"w": "god", "t": 17, "c": {"1": 6, "2": 4, "3": 2, "4": 5}}, {"w": "faith", "t": 16, "c": {"1": 2, "2": 13, "5": 1}}, {"w": "brothers", "t": 15, "c": {"1": 3, "2": 3, "3": 3, "4": 1, "5": 5}}, {"w": "lord", "t": 14, "c": {"1": 3, "2": 1, "4": 2, "5": 8}}, {"w": "works", "t": 12, "c": {"2": 12}}, {"w": "law", "t": 10, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 5, "4": 4}}, {"w": "good", "t": 7, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 3, "3": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "perfect", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 4, "3": 1}}, {"w": "rich", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 2, "2": 2, "5": 1}}, {"w": "evil", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1, "3": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "word", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 4, "3": 1}}, {"w": "tongue", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 4}}, {"w": "world", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1, "3": 1, "4": 2}}, {"w": "mercy", "t": 5, "c": {"2": 3, "3": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "fire", "t": 5, "c": {"3": 4, "5": 1}}, {"w": "earth", "t": 5, "c": {"5": 5}}, {"w": "wisdom", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 3}}, {"w": "humble", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 2, "4": 2}}, {"w": "tempted", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 4}}, {"w": "sin", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 2, "2": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "coming", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 1, "5": 3}}, {"w": "father", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 2, "2": 1, "3": 1}}, {"w": "partiality", "t": 4, "c": {"2": 3, "3": 1}}, {"w": "poor", "t": 4, "c": {"2": 4}}, {"w": "dead", "t": 4, "c": {"2": 4}}, {"w": "judge", "t": 4, "c": {"4": 3, "5": 1}}, {"w": "rain", "t": 4, "c": {"5": 4}}, {"w": "blessed", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 2, "5": 1}}, {"w": "life", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "4": 2}}, {"w": "love", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 2}}, {"w": "lust", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "truth", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "righteousness", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1, "3": 1}}, {"w": "doer", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "name", "t": 3, "c": {"2": 1, "5": 2}}, {"w": "scripture", "t": 3, "c": {"2": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "judgment", "t": 3, "c": {"2": 2, "3": 1}}, {"w": "peace", "t": 3, "c": {"2": 1, "3": 2}}, {"w": "justified", "t": 3, "c": {"2": 3}}, {"w": "fruit", "t": 3, "c": {"3": 1, "5": 2}}, {"w": "hearts", "t": 3, "c": {"4": 1, "5": 2}}, {"w": "patient", "t": 3, "c": {"5": 3}}, {"w": "pray", "t": 3, "c": {"5": 3}}, {"w": "sins", "t": 3, "c": {"5": 3}}, {"w": "jesus", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1}}, {"w": "christ", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1}}, {"w": "endurance", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 2}}, {"w": "double-minded", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "glory", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "death", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "gift", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 2}}, {"w": "anger", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 2}}, {"w": "hearer", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 2}}, {"w": "freedom", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1}}, {"w": "bridle", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1}}, {"w": "heart", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1}}, {"w": "religion", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 2}}, {"w": "pure", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1}}, {"w": "adultery", "t": 2, "c": {"2": 2}}, {"w": "abraham", "t": 2, "c": {"2": 2}}, {"w": "spirit", "t": 2, "c": {"2": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "stumble", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 2}}, {"w": "spring", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 2}}, {"w": "jealousy", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 2}}, {"w": "selfish", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 2}}, {"w": "ambition", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 2}}, {"w": "hypocrisy", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "pleasures", "t": 2, "c": {"4": 2}}, {"w": "war", "t": 2, "c": {"4": 2}}, {"w": "grace", "t": 2, "c": {"4": 2}}, {"w": "righteous", "t": 2, "c": {"5": 2}}, {"w": "sick", "t": 2, "c": {"5": 2}}, {"w": "prayer", "t": 2, "c": {"5": 2}}], "av": [{"w": "ask", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 2, "4": 3}}, {"w": "receive", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 3, "3": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "humble", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 2, "4": 2}}, {"w": "save", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1, "4": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "show", "t": 4, "c": {"2": 3, "3": 1}}, {"w": "commit", "t": 4, "c": {"2": 4}}, {"w": "judge", "t": 4, "c": {"4": 3, "5": 1}}, {"w": "love", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 2}}, {"w": "speak", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "murder", "t": 3, "c": {"2": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "pray", "t": 3, "c": {"5": 3}}, {"w": "bridle", "t": 2, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1}}, {"w": "believe", "t": 2, "c": {"2": 2}}, {"w": "stumble", "t": 2, "c": {"3": 2}}, {"w": "resist", "t": 2, "c": {"4": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "draw", "t": 2, "c": {"4": 2}}, {"w": "weep", "t": 2, "c": {"4": 1, "5": 1}}], "pr": [{"w": "you", "t": 73, "c": {"1": 4, "2": 23, "3": 3, "4": 25, "5": 18}}, {"w": "he", "t": 34, "c": {"1": 17, "2": 6, "4": 5, "5": 6}}, {"w": "your", "t": 31, "c": {"1": 3, "2": 3, "3": 1, "4": 10, "5": 14}}, {"w": "who", "t": 28, "c": {"1": 6, "2": 6, "3": 4, "4": 6, "5": 6}}, {"w": "him", "t": 21, "c": {"1": 4, "2": 5, "3": 1, "4": 2, "5": 9}}, {"w": "it", "t": 20, "c": {"1": 5, "2": 4, "3": 3, "4": 4, "5": 4}}, {"w": "his", "t": 15, "c": {"1": 9, "2": 2, "3": 2, "4": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "my", "t": 13, "c": {"1": 3, "2": 6, "3": 3, "5": 1}}, {"w": "one", "t": 11, "c": {"1": 2, "2": 3, "4": 2, "5": 4}}, {"w": "we", "t": 9, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 6, "4": 1, "5": 1}}, {"w": "our", "t": 5, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 2, "3": 2}}, {"w": "them", "t": 5, "c": {"2": 3, "5": 2}}, {"w": "himself", "t": 4, "c": {"1": 3, "4": 1}}, {"w": "they", "t": 4, "c": {"2": 1, "3": 2, "4": 1}}, {"w": "i", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "2": 2}}, {"w": "us", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1, "4": 1}}, {"w": "their", "t": 3, "c": {"1": 1, "3": 1, "5": 1}}]};
const GL = [{"w": "god", "n": 17, "d": "The Creator, Sustainer, and Ruler of all things, the one true Source from whom everything proceeds and for whom everything exists. James presents God as the generous Father who gives wisdom without holding it back, who does not tempt anyone with evil, and who opposes the proud but embraces the humble. He is not distant or indifferent. He is the Father of lights, the Measure of all reality, the unshifting foundation for the believer facing trials in a world full of fading illusions. For James, to know God is not mere intellectual knowledge. It is an intimate, personal relationship that shapes how you live, how you speak, and how you treat every single person around you.", "v": "Every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, with whom can be no variation nor turning shadow.", "r": "James 1:17", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "faith", "n": 16, "d": "A living trust in God that shows itself through action. This is the heartbeat of the entire letter. Faith is the engine of the soul, the active expectation that works through love. James is not against faith. He is against a faith that sits in a chair and never gets up. In the original language, this word carries a deep sense of personal conviction and reliance on God, the kind of trust that moves your feet, opens your wallet, and changes the way you treat people. True faith trusts in what God accomplished in the past, in His sovereignty over the present, and in His promise to restore all things in the future. Faith that does not produce visible fruit is not weak faith. James says it is dead faith.", "v": "Even so faith, if it has no works, is dead in itself.", "r": "James 2:17", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "brothers", "n": 15, "d": "Fellow believers in Christ, those who do the will of the Father, bound together by a sacred duty to bear one another's burdens. James uses this word more than almost any other. He says 'my brothers' and 'my beloved brothers' again and again. Even when he is correcting them sharply, he never stops calling them brothers. There is an old story about a traveler who saw a young boy carrying a smaller child on his back and said with pity, 'What a heavy burden you carry,' and the boy replied, 'He is not a burden, he is my brother.' That is the spirit James is calling for. A brother is not a project, not an inconvenience, not a weight. A brother is family, and you carry family with joy.", "v": "Count it all joy, my brothers, when you fall into various temptations.", "r": "James 1:2", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "lord", "n": 14, "d": "The supreme ruler and master over all things. James uses this title to remind us that God is in charge, not us. We do not control tomorrow, we do not decide the outcome of our plans, and we do not hold the final verdict on anyone. The Lord gives, the Lord judges, the Lord is coming back. When James says 'if the Lord wills,' he is not being superstitious. He is teaching us to hold our plans with open hands and let God be God.", "v": "For you ought to say, 'If the Lord wills, we will both live, and do this or that.'", "r": "James 4:15", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "works", "n": 12, "d": "The visible actions that demonstrate a genuine faith, the fruit of the hands. Every single time James uses this word, it appears in chapter 2, right in the middle of his most famous argument. He is not saying that works earn salvation. He is saying that if your faith is real, it will inevitably produce fruit. Works are the forensic evidence of a justified heart, the outward proof that something real has happened on the inside. Think of it this way: works are not the root of the tree, they are the fruit. But a tree with no fruit at all is a tree that has something seriously wrong on the inside.", "v": "You see that faith worked with his works, and by works faith was perfected.", "r": "James 2:22", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "law", "n": 10, "d": "The moral instruction of God, which James calls 'the royal law' and 'the perfect law of freedom.' In the original language, this word refers not merely to a list of rules but to the whole teaching of God that guides His people. James is clear: the law is not a prison. It is a perfect mirror that reveals who you really are, showing both the sin that disfigures you and the path toward restoration. For the one who has been made new by God, this law is not a heavy yoke but a delight, a balm for the soul. And when you obey it from the heart, it sets you free. Breaking one part of it makes you guilty of the whole.", "v": "However, if you fulfill the royal law according to the Scripture, 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself,' you do well.", "r": "James 2:8", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "good", "n": 7, "d": "That which aligns with God's character and purposes. James connects 'good' to gifts from above, to conduct that reflects wisdom, and to works that prove faith is alive. In a world that redefines good according to personal preference, James anchors it to the unchanging nature of God. If it comes from the Father of lights, it is good. If it does not, no matter how attractive it looks, it is not.", "v": "Who is wise and understanding among you? Let him show by his good conduct that his deeds are done in gentleness of wisdom.", "r": "James 3:13", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "perfect", "n": 5, "d": "Complete, mature, lacking nothing. In the original language, this word does not mean flawless in the way we usually think. It means fully developed, having reached the intended goal. James says that endurance must do its full work so that you may be perfect and complete. God is not looking for people who never fail. He is looking for people who keep growing, who let the trials finish their work, until they look more and more like Christ.", "v": "Let endurance have its perfect work, that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing.", "r": "James 1:4", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "rich", "n": 5, "d": "Those who possess material wealth. James does not condemn being rich. He condemns those who use their riches to oppress the poor, withhold wages from workers, and live in luxury while others suffer. He warns that riches are temporary, that gold corrodes, that fine garments get eaten by moths. The rich who trust in their wealth will fade away like a wildflower under the scorching sun. The real question is not how much you have, but what your wealth is doing to your soul and to the people around you.", "v": "Come now, you rich, weep and howl for your miseries that are coming on you.", "r": "James 5:1", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "evil", "n": 5, "d": "Anything that opposes the character and will of God. James traces evil back to its source: it does not come from God. God cannot be tempted by evil and He tempts no one. Evil grows from the inside out, from our own desires that pull us away. James also speaks of evil thoughts, evil deeds, and evil speech. The tongue, he says, is 'a world of iniquity.' Evil is not just the big, dramatic sins. It is the small, daily choices that slowly pull us away from the Lord.", "v": "Let no man say when he is tempted, 'I am tempted by God,' for God can't be tempted by evil, and he himself tempts no one.", "r": "James 1:13", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "word", "n": 5, "d": "The message and truth of God. James calls it 'the word of truth' by which God gave us new birth, and 'the implanted word' that has the power to save our souls. But he also says something that cuts deep: do not just listen to it. Do something with it. The person who hears the Word and does nothing is like someone who looks in a mirror, sees the mess, and walks away without fixing anything. The Word is meant to change you, not just inform you.", "v": "But be doers of the word, and not only hearers, deluding your own selves.", "r": "James 1:22", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "tongue", "n": 5, "d": "The organ of speech, used by James as a powerful symbol for the enormous influence of our words. In the original language, the word for mouth also carries the meaning of a blade or an edge, and that is exactly how James treats it. The tongue can be a sword that destroys or medicine that heals. He compares it to a rudder that steers a ship, a bit that controls a horse, and a tiny spark that sets an entire forest on fire. The tongue is small but it boasts of great things. No human being can tame it. It blesses God and curses people made in God's image. James is telling us: if you want to know the true condition of your heart, listen carefully to what comes out of your mouth.", "v": "So the tongue is also a little member, and boasts great things. See how a small fire can spread to a large forest!", "r": "James 3:5", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "world", "n": 5, "d": "The system of values, desires, and priorities that runs in opposition to God, a hostile environment for the soul of the believer. James draws a very sharp line: friendship with the world is hostility toward God. You cannot have it both ways. In the original language, this word refers not to the physical earth but to the organized arrangement of human life that has turned its back on the Creator. It is the mentality that says: get what you can, enjoy what you want, and answer to no one. To share in its common hope is to share in its common ruin.", "v": "You adulterers and adulteresses, don't you know that friendship with the world is hostility toward God?", "r": "James 4:4", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "mercy", "n": 5, "d": "Compassion shown to someone who does not deserve it. James says judgment is without mercy to the one who has shown no mercy, and then he adds one of the most beautiful lines in all of Scripture: mercy triumphs over judgment. If God dealt with us strictly by the rules, none of us would stand. But mercy steps in and says: I know what you deserve, and I choose to give you something better. James wants us to extend that same gift to others.", "v": "For judgment is without mercy to him who has shown no mercy. Mercy triumphs over judgment.", "r": "James 2:13", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "fire", "n": 5, "d": "James uses fire as a vivid image of destruction and purification. The tongue is a fire, set ablaze by the very pit of hell. The corrosion of hoarded wealth will eat the flesh of the rich like fire. In the ancient world, fire was both essential and terrifying. One small flame could warm a family or burn down an entire city. James is saying: your words carry that same double potential. Handle them with the seriousness they deserve.", "v": "And the tongue is a fire. The world of iniquity among our members is the tongue, which defiles the whole body, and sets on fire the course of nature, and is set on fire by Gehenna.", "r": "James 3:6", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "wisdom", "n": 4, "d": "The ability to see life from God's perspective and act accordingly. James talks about two kinds of wisdom. One is earthly, driven by selfish ambition and jealousy, and it produces disorder and every kind of evil. It is the kind of wisdom that builds platforms instead of people, that turns churches into businesses and leaders into merchants. The other comes from above: it is pure, peaceful, gentle, reasonable, full of mercy and good fruits. In the original language, this word describes not academic intelligence but practical skill for living well before God. If you lack it, James says, ask God. He gives generously and without reproach.", "v": "But the wisdom that is from above is first pure, then peaceful, gentle, reasonable, full of mercy and good fruits, without partiality, and without hypocrisy.", "r": "James 3:17", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "humble", "n": 4, "d": "Lowly in position or spirit, willing to place yourself under God's authority. James commands us to humble ourselves before the Lord, promising that He will lift us up. The brother in humble circumstances should take pride in his high spiritual position, while the rich should recognize how small they really are. In the original language, this word carries the idea of making yourself low, of bending the knee not because you are forced but because you understand who God is and who you are.", "v": "Humble yourselves in the sight of the Lord, and he will exalt you.", "r": "James 4:10", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "temptation", "n": 4, "d": "A trial or enticement to do evil. In the original language, this word has a double meaning: it can refer to an external test that strengthens your faith or an internal pull toward sin. James makes a critical distinction: God tests us to refine us, but He never entices us to sin. That comes from our own desires, which conceive sin, and sin when fully grown produces death. A child may see the scalpel and think it is an attack, but the Father sees a surgeon carefully removing a deadly tumor. Trials are God's instruments of providence, designed to produce a deeper dependence on Him. Understanding where temptation comes from is the first step to resisting it.", "v": "But each one is tempted when he is drawn away by his own lust and enticed.", "r": "James 1:14", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "sin", "n": 4, "d": "Missing the mark of God's standard. James traces the entire lifecycle of sin like a poisonous fruit growing on a tree: desire gives birth to sin, and sin when it is fully grown gives birth to death. It begins as a deceptive internal craving, something that looks attractive and harmless, but once it is conceived it brings forth destruction. He also says that knowing the right thing to do and not doing it is sin. This is a devastating statement. Sin is not only the bad things we do. It is also the good things we refuse to do. James leaves no room for comfortable passivity.", "v": "To him therefore who knows to do good and doesn't do it, to him it is sin.", "r": "James 4:17", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "father", "n": 4, "d": "God as the loving source and origin of all good things. James calls Him 'the Father of lights,' a title found nowhere else in Scripture. It means that God is the origin of every form of light, every star, every truth, every moment of clarity. And unlike the sun and the moon that cast shifting shadows, the Father has no variation, no change, no dark side. He is constantly, eternally, reliably good.", "v": "Every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, with whom can be no variation nor turning shadow.", "r": "James 1:17", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "partiality", "n": 4, "d": "Treating people differently based on their outward appearance, wealth, or social status. In the original language, this word literally means 'to lift the face,' as in giving someone a favorable look based on who they are, not on what is right. James says this is incompatible with genuine faith. If a man with a gold ring walks into the assembly and gets the best seat while the poor man is told to stand in the corner, the church has become a court of unjust judges.", "v": "My brothers, don't hold the faith of our glorious Lord Jesus Christ with partiality.", "r": "James 2:1", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "poor", "n": 4, "d": "Those who lack material resources. James has a special tenderness toward the poor. He says God chose the poor of this world to be rich in faith and heirs of the kingdom. God, in His sovereignty, determines the circumstances of every life, and He often chooses the lowly to receive the greatest spiritual inheritance. In the first century church, the poor were being dishonored and pushed aside in favor of the wealthy. James says this is backwards. God does not measure people by the thickness of their wallets. He measures them by the depth of their trust in Him.", "v": "Listen, my beloved brothers. Didn't God choose those who are poor in this world to be rich in faith and heirs of the Kingdom which he promised to those who love him?", "r": "James 2:5", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "dead", "n": 4, "d": "Lifeless, without breath, without movement. Every time James uses this word in chapter 2, he is talking about faith. Faith without works is dead. Not weak. Not sleeping. Dead. Like a body without a spirit. He is not being dramatic for the sake of it. He is warning us that a confession of faith that produces no visible change in how you live, how you love, and how you treat people is not a living faith at all. It is a corpse with a name tag.", "v": "For as the body apart from the spirit is dead, even so faith apart from works is dead.", "r": "James 2:26", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "judge", "n": 4, "d": "One who passes a verdict or sentence. James warns us not to set ourselves up as judges over our brothers. When you speak evil against a brother, you are placing yourself above the law and above God. There is only one Lawgiver and Judge, the Risen Lord who holds universal authority to evaluate every thought and action with absolute impartiality. He is the one who can save and destroy. James is not saying we should never evaluate right from wrong. He is saying: do not usurp the throne that belongs to God alone. The pride of making yourself the measure of all things is the oldest sin in existence. The Judge is standing at the door, and that should change how we treat every person we encounter.", "v": "Only one is the lawgiver, who is able to save and to destroy. But who are you to judge another?", "r": "James 4:12", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "earth", "n": 5, "d": "The physical ground, the world where we live our temporary lives. In chapter 5, James uses the earth as the stage where both injustice and patience play out. The rich have lived in luxury on the earth. The farmer waits for the precious fruit of the earth. Elijah prayed and the earth produced its fruit again. For James, the earth is a temporary classroom, not a permanent home. What matters is not what you accumulate here but what you are becoming here.", "v": "He prayed again, and the sky gave rain, and the earth produced its fruit.", "r": "James 5:18", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "endurance", "n": 2, "d": "The capacity to remain under pressure without giving up. In the original language, this word literally means 'to stay under,' to bear the weight of the trial instead of running away from it. James says endurance must have its complete work so that you may be mature and whole. Think of it as spiritual muscle. You do not build it in comfort. You build it in the very moment you want to quit and you choose to keep going anyway.", "v": "Let endurance have its perfect work, that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing.", "r": "James 1:4", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "gift", "n": 2, "d": "Something given freely, without being earned. James says every good gift and every perfect gift comes down from the Father of lights. The word for 'gift' and the word for 'perfect gift' in the original language are actually two different words. One refers to the act of giving and the other to the thing given. Together they mean: both the generous impulse of God and the actual blessing He sends are entirely from above. Nothing good in your life is self-made.", "v": "Every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights.", "r": "James 1:17", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "double-minded", "n": 2, "d": "A person who tries to go in two directions at the same time. In the original language, this word literally means 'two-souled.' James uses it twice, in chapter 1 for the person who prays but doubts, and in chapter 4 for the person who tries to be a friend of both God and the world. This person is unstable in everything. James is saying: make up your mind. You cannot sit on the fence forever. Either draw near to God with everything you have, or admit that you are still divided.", "v": "He is a double-minded man, unstable in all his ways.", "r": "James 1:8", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "blessed", "n": 3, "d": "Deeply happy in a way that circumstances cannot take away. James declares blessed the person who endures temptation, because when they have been proven genuine, they will receive the crown of life. He also calls blessed those who have suffered with perseverance. This is not the happiness the world advertises. This is the quiet, unshakable joy that comes from knowing your trial has a purpose and your God has not forgotten you.", "v": "Blessed is a person who endures temptation, for when he has been approved, he will receive the crown of life which the Lord promised to those who love him.", "r": "James 1:12", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "life", "n": 3, "d": "Human existence in its brevity and also in its eternal significance. James says our life is a vapor, a mist that appears for a little while and vanishes. But he also speaks of the crown of life, the eternal reward for those who endure. The contrast is powerful: your time on this earth is short, but the decisions you make here have consequences that last forever. Live accordingly.", "v": "For what is your life? For you are a vapor that appears for a little time and then vanishes away.", "r": "James 4:14", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "love", "n": 3, "d": "Active, self-giving care for another person. James connects love directly to the royal law: 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself.' Love in this letter is not a feeling. It is a decision to treat others the way God has treated you. It means not giving the best seat to the rich man while ignoring the poor one. It means feeding the hungry brother, not just telling him to stay warm.", "v": "However, if you fulfill the royal law according to the Scripture, 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself,' you do well.", "r": "James 2:8", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "lust", "n": 3, "d": "A strong desire that pulls you toward sin. In the original language, this word refers to any overpowering craving, not only sexual desire. It is the internal magnet that draws you away from God and toward self-destruction. James says each person is tempted when they are dragged away by their own lust. The enemy does not always need to do much. Our own desires, when we let them run wild, are enough to bring us down.", "v": "But each one is tempted when he is drawn away by his own lust and enticed.", "r": "James 1:14", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "truth", "n": 3, "d": "The reality of things as God sees them. James speaks of the 'word of truth' by which God gave us spiritual birth. He also closes his letter with the concern for anyone who wanders from the truth. Truth in James is not a philosophical concept you debate in a classroom. It is the firm ground you stand on, and when someone steps off it, the loving thing to do is go after them and bring them back.", "v": "Brothers, if any among you wanders from the truth and someone turns him back, let him know that he who turns a sinner from the error of his way will save a soul from death.", "r": "James 5:19-20", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "righteousness", "n": 3, "d": "Right standing before God, doing what is morally correct. James says the anger of man does not produce the righteousness of God. In other words, your outrage, no matter how justified it feels, does not accomplish what God is looking for. Instead, the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace by those who make peace. If you want to see righteousness grow, plant seeds of reconciliation, not seeds of conflict.", "v": "Now the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace by those who make peace.", "r": "James 3:18", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "doer", "n": 3, "d": "A person who acts on what they hear. This word is uniquely important in James. He contrasts the doer with the hearer. The hearer listens but does nothing. The doer hears and obeys. James says this person will be blessed in what they do. Christianity, for James, is not a spectator sport. You are called to get on the field, get your hands dirty, and live out the faith you profess.", "v": "But he who looks into the perfect law of freedom and continues, not being a hearer who forgets but a doer of the work, this man will be blessed in what he does.", "r": "James 1:25", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "scripture", "n": 3, "d": "The written Word of God, the sacred text. James quotes Scripture directly and treats it as the final authority. He cites 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself,' the story of Abraham, and the proverb about God opposing the proud. For James, Scripture is not optional reading. It is the voice of God put on paper, and it settles every argument.", "v": "So the Scripture was fulfilled which says, 'Abraham believed God, and it was accounted to him as righteousness.'", "r": "James 2:23", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "judgment", "n": 3, "d": "The evaluation and verdict that God renders. James warns that teachers will receive a stricter judgment, that showing no mercy invites judgment without mercy, and that the Judge is standing at the door. This is not meant to terrorize us but to wake us up. We will give an account. The way we treat people, the words we speak, the opportunities we waste. Judgment is real, and it begins with the household of God.", "v": "Let not many of you be teachers, my brothers, knowing that we will receive heavier judgment.", "r": "James 3:1", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "peace", "n": 3, "d": "Harmony with God and with others. The wisdom from above is peaceable, and the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace by peacemakers. James is writing to people full of conflicts, fights, and bitter jealousy. His prescription is not more arguing but more peacemaking. In the original language, this word carries the idea of wholeness, completeness, everything being in its right place. Peace is not the absence of problems. It is the presence of God in the middle of them.", "v": "Now the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace by those who make peace.", "r": "James 3:18", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "justified", "n": 3, "d": "Declared righteous, shown to be genuine. James uses Abraham and Rahab as his two witnesses. Abraham was justified by works when he offered Isaac. Rahab was justified by works when she hid the spies. James is not contradicting Paul. He is saying that a faith which has been declared genuine by God will inevitably show itself through obedient action. The verdict was already given in heaven, but the evidence is displayed on earth.", "v": "You see then that by works a man is justified, and not only by faith.", "r": "James 2:24", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "fruit", "n": 3, "d": "The visible result of what is planted inside. James talks about the fruit of righteousness sown in peace, and the farmer who waits patiently for the precious fruit of the earth. Fruit takes time. It requires the right soil, the right rain, and above all, patience. James is telling us: do not rush God's process. Plant the right seeds, water them with obedience, and trust that the harvest will come in due season.", "v": "Behold, the farmer waits for the precious fruit of the earth, being patient over it, until it receives the early and late rain.", "r": "James 5:7", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "patience", "n": 3, "d": "The ability to wait without complaining, trusting God's timing. Patience is the fruit of tribulation, the spiritual muscle that grows only under pressure. James uses the farmer as his great illustration. The farmer plants and then waits for the early rain and the late rain. He does not dig up the seed every morning to check on it. He trusts the process. In the same way, believers must wait for the coming of the Lord with steady hearts, satisfied in the knowledge that God's timing is perfect even when our circumstances scream otherwise. Patience is not passive. It is an active decision to keep trusting when every part of you wants to give up.", "v": "You also be patient. Establish your hearts, for the coming of the Lord is at hand.", "r": "James 5:8", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "prayer", "n": 5, "d": "Direct communication with God, the holy use of the mouth in its highest calling. James closes his letter with one of the most practical teachings on prayer in all of Scripture. Are you suffering? Pray. Are you cheerful? Sing praises. Are you sick? Call the elders and let them pray over you. The prayer of faith will save the sick. The persistent prayer of a righteous person is powerfully effective, as Elijah proved when he prayed in step with the Father's determined will and the skies obeyed. Prayer is not a spare tire you pull out in emergencies. It is the steering wheel of the Christian life. But it requires a heart that asks in faith, without the double mindedness that characterizes those who do not truly trust God's sovereign care.", "v": "The insistent prayer of a righteous person is powerfully effective.", "r": "James 5:16", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "grace", "n": 2, "d": "The undeserved favor of God toward those who do not merit it. James says God gives more grace, and He gives it to the humble. The proud get resistance. The humble get grace. Think of it this way: the Word of God is like a sword that pierces the conscience and exposes the sin, and grace is the balm that heals the wound afterward. This is the economy of heaven: the less you think of yourself, the more God pours into you. Grace in James is not a license to do whatever you want. It is the saving power that enables you to do what you could never do on your own.", "v": "But he gives more grace. Therefore it says, 'God resists the proud, but gives grace to the humble.'", "r": "James 4:6", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "religion", "n": 2, "d": "The outward practice and expression of devotion to God. James uses this word to make a devastating point: if you think you are religious but do not control your tongue, your religion is worthless. Then he defines pure and undefiled religion in the simplest possible terms: visit orphans and widows in their trouble, and keep yourself unstained from the world. Real religion, for James, is not about rituals, appearances, or impressive words. It is about what you do with your hands and how clean you keep your heart.", "v": "Pure religion and undefiled before our God and Father is this: to visit the fatherless and widows in their affliction, and to keep oneself unstained by the world.", "r": "James 1:27", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "pure", "n": 2, "d": "Clean, unmixed, free from contamination. The wisdom from above is first of all pure. Pure religion is to keep yourself unstained by the world. In the original language, this word carries the idea of something so clean that it is fit to be brought into the presence of God. James is saying: before you worry about being peaceful, gentle, or merciful, start by being pure. Purity is the foundation on which everything else is built.", "v": "But the wisdom that is from above is first pure, then peaceful, gentle, reasonable.", "r": "James 3:17", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "anger", "n": 2, "d": "A strong emotional response to perceived injustice. James warns: be slow to anger, because human anger does not produce the righteousness that God desires. In the original language, this word refers to a settled, burning indignation, not just a flash of irritation. Many believers justify their rage by calling it 'righteous anger,' but James is clear: before you get angry, make sure you have listened first and spoken carefully. Your fury, no matter how justified it feels to you, is rarely doing what you think it is doing for the kingdom of God.", "v": "For the anger of man doesn't produce the righteousness of God.", "r": "James 1:20", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "freedom", "n": 2, "d": "Liberty that comes from obeying God's truth. James calls the law of God 'the perfect law of freedom.' This sounds like a contradiction until you understand what he means. When you live according to God's design, you are free from the slavery of sin, free from the tyranny of selfish desires, and free to become the person you were created to be. Freedom is not doing whatever you want. Freedom is wanting what God wants and having the power to do it.", "v": "But he who looks into the perfect law of freedom and continues, not being a hearer who forgets but a doer of the work, this man will be blessed in what he does.", "r": "James 1:25", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "jesus", "n": 2, "d": "The personal name of the Son of God. James mentions Jesus by name only twice in his entire letter, but His presence fills every page. When James speaks of the royal law of love, of mercy triumphing over judgment, of humbling yourself before the Lord, he is echoing the teachings of the very brother he grew up with. James did not believe in Jesus during His earthly ministry. But after the resurrection, everything changed. The servant became the brother, and the brother became the Lord.", "v": "James, a servant of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ, to the twelve tribes which are in the Dispersion: Greetings.", "r": "James 1:1", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "christ", "n": 2, "d": "The title meaning 'the Anointed One,' the promised Messiah. When James says 'our glorious Lord Jesus Christ,' he is making a staggering claim. The carpenter from Nazareth, the one James ate meals with, argued with, and watched grow up, is the Lord of glory. For James, faith in Christ is not an abstract theological exercise. It is personal, concrete, and it changes the way you treat every person who walks through the door of your assembly.", "v": "My brothers, don't hold the faith of our glorious Lord Jesus Christ with partiality.", "r": "James 2:1", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "heart", "n": 3, "d": "The internal core of a person where thoughts, desires, and decisions are formed. James presents the heart as a battlefield where two opposing armies are in constant conflict: the pull of selfish desires and the call of God's grace. It is from the heart that wars and conflicts originate. It is the heart that must be purified, the heart that must be established, the heart that the double minded person has failed to surrender. James is saying: the real problem is never just what you did or what you said. The real problem is always what is happening inside, in that hidden place where only you and God can see.", "v": "Cleanse your hands, you sinners. Purify your hearts, you double-minded.", "r": "James 4:8", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "tempted", "n": 4, "d": "To be drawn toward sin or tested by difficult circumstances. James uses this word four times in the first chapter alone, making a critical distinction between two very different experiences. God tests His children to strengthen them, the way a trainer pushes an athlete to build endurance. But God never entices anyone toward evil. That enticement comes from within, from our own desires that pull us away from what we know is right. When you feel the pull, recognize the source. It is not God trying to destroy you. It is your own flesh trying to deceive you.", "v": "Let no man say when he is tempted, 'I am tempted by God,' for God can't be tempted by evil, and he himself tempts no one.", "r": "James 1:13", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "coming", "n": 4, "d": "The return of the Lord Jesus Christ to the earth, the blessed hope of every believer. James uses this word primarily in chapter 5, urging believers to be patient as they wait for the Lord's arrival. The coming of the Lord is not a distant theological concept for James. It is an imminent reality that should shape the way we live, the way we endure suffering, and the way we treat one another. The farmer waits patiently because he knows the harvest is certain. The believer waits patiently because the Judge is standing at the door.", "v": "Be patient therefore, brothers, until the coming of the Lord.", "r": "James 5:7", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "rain", "n": 4, "d": "The early and late rains that nourish the crops in the land of Israel. James uses rain as part of his illustration of the patient farmer who plants and then waits, trusting that the seasons will do their work. In the ancient agricultural world, the early rain softened the soil for planting and the late rain brought the harvest to maturity. Without both, the crop would fail. James is telling us: God sends what you need in the season you need it. Your job is to plant, to be faithful, and to wait for the rain that only He can provide.", "v": "Behold, the farmer waits for the precious fruit of the earth, being patient over it, until it receives the early and late rain.", "r": "James 5:7", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "name", "n": 3, "d": "The identity and reputation of a person, and especially the sacred name of Christ. James says the rich blaspheme the honorable name by which believers are called, and he instructs the elders to anoint the sick in the name of the Lord. In the biblical world, a name was not just a label. It carried the full weight of a person's character, authority, and power. To act in the name of the Lord is to act under His authority, with His backing, and for His glory.", "v": "Don't they blaspheme the honorable name by which you are called?", "r": "James 2:7", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "hearts", "n": 3, "d": "The internal core of a person where thoughts, desires, and decisions are formed. James commands us to purify our hearts and to establish them, because the coming of the Lord is near. The heart is where the real battle takes place. It is the battlefield where selfish desires clash with the call of God's grace. James is saying: the real problem is never just what you did or what you said. The real problem is always what is happening inside, in that hidden place where only you and God can see.", "v": "Cleanse your hands, you sinners. Purify your hearts, you double-minded.", "r": "James 4:8", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "patient", "n": 3, "d": "Willing to wait without losing hope or complaining. James calls believers to be patient until the coming of the Lord, using the farmer as his model. The farmer does not dig up the seed every morning to check on it. He trusts the process. He trusts the rain. He trusts the seasons. Patience is not sitting around doing nothing. It is active faithfulness in the waiting, the steady refusal to give up even when the harvest seems impossibly far away.", "v": "You also be patient. Establish your hearts, for the coming of the Lord is at hand.", "r": "James 5:8", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "pray", "n": 3, "d": "To communicate directly with God, bringing your needs, your gratitude, and your burdens before Him. James gives the clearest set of instructions on prayer in the entire New Testament: if you suffer, pray. If you are cheerful, sing praises. If you are sick, call the elders. And pray for one another. Prayer is not reserved for emergencies or special occasions. It is the constant rhythm of the Christian life, the breathing of the soul that keeps us connected to the Father of lights.", "v": "Is any among you suffering? Let him pray. Is any cheerful? Let him sing praises.", "r": "James 5:13", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "sins", "n": 3, "d": "Acts of disobedience against the will and character of God. James connects sins to confession, healing, and restoration. He instructs believers to confess their sins to one another and to pray for one another so that they may be healed. Sin left in the dark grows. Sin brought into the light loses its power. The community of faith is meant to be a place where confession is safe, where forgiveness is real, and where no one has to carry the weight of their failures alone.", "v": "Confess your sins to one another, and pray for one another, that you may be healed.", "r": "James 5:16", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "glory", "n": 2, "d": "The visible splendor, honor, and weight of God's presence. James speaks of our glorious Lord Jesus Christ, using a phrase that places the full majesty of God upon the carpenter from Nazareth. He also says the rich will fade away like a flower in the grass, losing all their earthly glory. The contrast is intentional: human glory is temporary, like wildflowers under the scorching sun. The glory of the Lord is eternal, unchanging, and it belongs to the one who humbles himself under God's mighty hand.", "v": "My brothers, don't hold the faith of our glorious Lord Jesus Christ with partiality.", "r": "James 2:1", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "death", "n": 2, "d": "The final consequence of sin when it has fully matured. James traces a terrifying progression: desire gives birth to sin, and sin when fully grown gives birth to death. But he also closes his letter with a promise of hope: the one who turns a sinner from the error of his way will save a soul from death. Death in James is not just physical. It is the total separation from the life that God intended for His creatures. And the antidote is always the same: repentance, confession, and the restoring grace of the community of faith.", "v": "Then the lust, when it has conceived, bears sin. The sin, when it is full grown, produces death.", "r": "James 1:15", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "hearer", "n": 2, "d": "A person who listens to the Word of God but does not act on it. James says that if anyone is a hearer and not a doer, that person is like someone who looks in a mirror, sees their reflection, and immediately forgets what they looked like. The hearer is not ignorant. They know the truth. They have heard it clearly. But knowing and doing are two very different things. James is warning us: the Word of God was not given to inform you. It was given to transform you.", "v": "But be doers of the word, and not only hearers, deluding your own selves.", "r": "James 1:22", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "bridle", "n": 2, "d": "A restraint placed on a horse's mouth to control and direct the animal. James uses the bridle as a powerful illustration of self-control. If you can bridle your tongue, you can bridle your whole body. The bridle does not destroy the horse. It directs it. In the same way, controlling your speech does not silence you. It channels your words toward what is constructive, truthful, and honoring to God.", "v": "If anyone among you thinks himself to be religious while he doesn't bridle his tongue, but deceives his heart, this man's religion is worthless.", "r": "James 1:26", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "adultery", "n": 2, "d": "Unfaithfulness in the most intimate relationship. James uses this word not to describe a physical act but a spiritual betrayal. He calls those who befriend the world 'adulterers and adulteresses,' borrowing the language of the Old Testament prophets who compared Israel's idolatry to marital unfaithfulness. When you give your deepest loyalty to the values and systems of this world instead of to God, you are committing spiritual adultery. You are breaking the covenant with the one who loved you first.", "v": "You adulterers and adulteresses, don't you know that friendship with the world is hostility toward God?", "r": "James 4:4", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "abraham", "n": 2, "d": "The patriarch of the faith, the father of the nation of Israel. James holds Abraham up as the ultimate example of living faith. Abraham believed God, and it was credited to him as righteousness. But then his faith was proven genuine when he offered his son Isaac on the altar. Abraham did not earn his standing with God through that act. He demonstrated it. His obedience was the visible evidence of an invisible trust that had already been declared righteous by God.", "v": "Wasn't Abraham our father justified by works, in that he offered up Isaac his son on the altar?", "r": "James 2:21", "ck": "the_living_faith"}, {"w": "spirit", "n": 2, "d": "The immaterial part of a person, or the Holy Spirit of God. James says the body without the spirit is dead, using it as a comparison: faith without works is equally lifeless. He also speaks of the spirit that God made to dwell in us, which yearns jealously for our complete devotion. The spirit is the breath of life that animates everything. Without it, the body is a corpse. Without works, faith is the same.", "v": "For as the body apart from the spirit is dead, even so faith apart from works is dead.", "r": "James 2:26", "ck": "the_father_of_lights"}, {"w": "stumble", "n": 2, "d": "To fall into sin or error. James says we all stumble in many ways, and if anyone does not stumble in what they say, that person is perfect, able to bridle the whole body. The word 'stumble' is honest and compassionate. It does not describe a deliberate dive into evil. It describes the trip, the fall, the moment when you lose your footing. James acknowledges that perfection is impossible for us. But he also says that the area where we stumble most is our speech, and that is where the greatest growth must happen.", "v": "For in many things we all stumble. If anyone doesn't stumble in word, he is a perfect man.", "r": "James 3:2", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "spring", "n": 2, "d": "A natural source of water flowing from the ground. James asks: does a spring send out fresh water and bitter water from the same opening? The answer is obvious: no. A single source produces a single kind of water. James is using nature to expose the hypocrisy of using the same mouth to bless God and curse people. If your words are sometimes sweet and sometimes poisonous, something is wrong at the source. The spring needs to be purified, and that purification can only happen from the inside out.", "v": "Does a spring send out from the same opening fresh and bitter water?", "r": "James 3:11", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "jealousy", "n": 2, "d": "A bitter resentment toward the success, position, or blessings of others. James connects jealousy directly to earthly, unspiritual, demonic wisdom. Where there is bitter jealousy and selfish ambition, there is disorder and every kind of evil practice. Jealousy is the poison that destroys community from the inside. It whispers: why does he have what I deserve? Why was she chosen and not me? James is clear: this does not come from God. It comes from below.", "v": "But if you have bitter jealousy and selfish ambition in your heart, don't boast and don't lie against the truth.", "r": "James 3:14", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "selfish", "n": 2, "d": "Concerned only with your own advantage, indifferent to the needs of others. James pairs 'selfish ambition' with jealousy as the twin marks of earthly wisdom. Selfish ambition is the engine behind the kind of leadership that builds platforms instead of people, that uses the church as a launching pad for personal fame, and that measures success by numbers rather than by faithfulness. James says: where this exists, expect chaos, division, and the collapse of everything that matters.", "v": "But if you have bitter jealousy and selfish ambition in your heart, don't boast and don't lie against the truth.", "r": "James 3:14", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "ambition", "n": 2, "d": "The drive to advance, to climb, to gain a position of influence. In the original language, this word was used to describe the tactics of a politician who would do anything to win an election: bribery, manipulation, empty promises. James is not condemning the desire to serve God effectively. He is condemning the kind of ambition that is willing to lie, manipulate, and step on others to get to the top. The wisdom from above does not compete. It serves. It does not promote itself. It lifts others up.", "v": "This wisdom is not that which comes down from above, but is earthly, sensual, and demonic.", "r": "James 3:15", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "hypocrisy", "n": 2, "d": "The act of pretending to be something you are not. In the original language, this word comes from the world of theater, where an actor would put on a mask and play a role on stage. James says the wisdom from above is 'without hypocrisy,' meaning it is genuine, transparent, and real. A hypocrite blesses God on Sunday and curses people on Monday. A hypocrite quotes Scripture with their mouth while their heart is far from God. James is calling for authenticity: let your inside match your outside.", "v": "But the wisdom that is from above is first pure, then peaceful, gentle, reasonable, full of mercy and good fruits, without partiality, and without hypocrisy.", "r": "James 3:17", "ck": "the_wisdom_from_above"}, {"w": "pleasures", "n": 2, "d": "The desires and cravings that drive human behavior when God is not at the center. James says the source of wars and fights among believers is their own pleasures that wage war inside them. In the original language, this word is closely related to the idea of sensory gratification, the relentless pursuit of what feels good in the moment without regard for its consequences. James is not saying that all enjoyment is sinful. He is saying that when pleasure becomes the compass of your life instead of the will of God, it will inevitably lead to conflict, covetousness, and destruction.", "v": "Where do wars and fightings among you come from? Don't they come from your pleasures that war in your members?", "r": "James 4:1", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "war", "n": 2, "d": "Conflict, fighting, and hostility, both within the individual and within the community. James opens chapter 4 by identifying the root of all relational destruction: internal war. The pleasures inside you are at war. And that internal war spills out into external fights with brothers and sisters. The irony is devastating: people who have been saved by the Prince of Peace are tearing each other apart because of uncontrolled desires. James says the solution is not better conflict management. It is the humility to submit your desires to God and let Him be the Lord of your longings.", "v": "Where do wars and fightings among you come from?", "r": "James 4:1", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "righteous", "n": 2, "d": "A person who lives in right standing before God, whose life aligns with the character and will of the Lord. James says the persistent prayer of a righteous person is powerfully effective, and he uses Elijah as his example. Elijah was not a superhero. He was a man with a nature just like ours. But he prayed in alignment with the will of God, and heaven responded. To be righteous in James is not to be sinless. It is to be surrendered, to be the kind of person who brings everything to God in prayer and trusts Him with the outcome.", "v": "The insistent prayer of a righteous person is powerfully effective.", "r": "James 5:16", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}, {"w": "sick", "n": 2, "d": "Those who are physically ill or spiritually weakened. James instructs the sick to call for the elders of the church, who should pray over them and anoint them with oil in the name of the Lord. This instruction connects three things that the modern world often separates: the body, the community, and the spiritual life. Healing in James is not a solo act. It involves the humility to ask for help, the presence of mature believers, the confession of sin, and the prayer of faith. God does not promise that every sick person will be immediately healed, but He does promise that the prayer of faith matters and that He is listening.", "v": "Is any among you sick? Let him call for the elders of the assembly, and let them pray over him, anointing him with oil in the name of the Lord.", "r": "James 5:14", "ck": "the_humble_heart"}];
const CATS = {"the_father_of_lights": {"label": "The Father of Lights", "desc": "James begins his letter by pointing us to the source of everything good. God is not a distant idea or a philosophical concept. He is the Father of lights, the one from whom every good gift and every perfect gift descends. There is no shadow in Him, no variation, no dark corner. He gives wisdom without reproach. He chose to give us new birth through the word of truth. He is the Lawgiver, the Judge, the one who stands at the door. Every word in this category reveals who God is in the letter of James: generous, holy, merciful, unchanging, and absolutely sovereign over all things. When you know who He is, everything else falls into place.", "src": "James 1:17, 'the Father of lights, with whom can be no variation'"}, "the_living_faith": {"label": "The Living Faith", "desc": "This is the engine of the entire letter. James refuses to let faith remain a private opinion or a Sunday confession. He grabs it by the collar and drags it into the real world. Can faith save you if it produces nothing? Can you say 'be warm and be filled' to a hungry brother and call that faith? Even the demons believe, and they tremble. James is not the enemy of faith. He is the enemy of a faith that sits down and never stands up. Every word in this category describes what genuine faith looks like when it puts on its work clothes: endurance, obedience, action, justice, and love that you can actually see with your eyes.", "src": "James 2:17, 'even so faith, if it has no works, is dead in itself'"}, "the_wisdom_from_above": {"label": "The Wisdom from Above", "desc": "James knows that the Christian life requires more than good intentions. It requires wisdom, the kind that does not come from a university or a self-help book. Earthly wisdom is jealous, selfish, and full of disorder. The wisdom from above is pure, peaceful, gentle, reasonable, full of mercy and good fruits, without partiality and without hypocrisy. This category gathers the words that describe how we speak, how we teach, how we handle conflict, and how we discern the difference between what sounds smart and what is actually true. The tongue, the fire, peace, truth, purity. These are the instruments that wisdom uses when it takes control of a life.", "src": "James 3:17, 'the wisdom from above is first pure, then peaceful'"}, "the_humble_heart": {"label": "The Humble Heart", "desc": "If the Father of Lights is the source, and living faith is the engine, and heavenly wisdom is the guide, then the humble heart is the soil in which all of it grows. James draws a relentless contrast between pride and humility, between the arrogance of the rich oppressor and the quiet trust of the suffering believer, between friendship with the world and submission to God. Every word in this category describes the posture of a life that has stopped fighting God and started resting in His hands: humility, patience, prayer, confession, and the willingness to wait for the Lord even when the wait feels unbearable. God resists the proud, but He pours His grace on the humble. That is the invitation James extends from the first chapter to the last.", "src": "James 4:10, 'Humble yourselves in the sight of the Lord, and he will exalt you'"}};
const CM = {"1": {"title": "Faith, Provision and Silence in the Christian Life", "sections": [{"t": "Introduction", "c": "Beloved brothers and sisters, there is a question that every honest Christian must face at some point in their walk with the Lord: Is my faith real? Not real in the sense of whether I believe certain doctrines to be true, because even the demons believe and they tremble. The question goes deeper than that. Is my faith the kind that changes the way I respond when the phone rings at two in the morning with bad news? Is it the kind that shapes how I treat the person who has nothing to offer me in return? Is it the kind that holds me steady when everything around me is falling apart? The writer of this letter understood that question better than most. He calls himself simply 'James, a servant of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ.' The evidence of history and Scripture points to James the brother of Jesus, a man who grew up in the same house as the Messiah and yet did not believe in Him during His earthly ministry. It was only after the resurrection, when the risen Christ appeared to him personally, that everything changed. The skeptic became a servant. The brother became a disciple. And the man who once doubted wrote a letter so practical, so direct, and so uncompromising that Martin Luther himself struggled with it. James writes to the twelve tribes scattered abroad, to Jewish believers dispersed throughout the Roman world, and his message is devastatingly simple: if your faith is real, it will show. This first chapter lays the foundation for everything that follows. It moves through three great themes: faith that endures through trials and receives wisdom from God, the provision of a Father who gives every good gift, and the discipline of learning to listen before we speak and to live what we hear."}, {"t": "Faith, Patience and Wisdom: The Science of Believing (James 1:1-12)", "c": "James wastes no time with pleasantries. His very first instruction is one of the most counterintuitive commands in all of Scripture: count it all joy when you fall into various trials. Not if, but when. And not some joy, but all joy. How is this possible? Because faith has its own science, its own logic that operates differently from the logic of this world. The worldly mind says: avoid pain at all costs. The mind of faith says: this pain has a purpose, and the God who allowed it is trustworthy. The testing of your faith, James says, produces endurance. And endurance must have its complete work so that you may be perfect and complete, lacking in nothing. Think about that for a moment. The word 'perfect' here does not mean sinless. In the original language it carries the sense of being fully developed, fully mature, having reached the goal for which you were designed. And the only way to reach that maturity is through the furnace of trial. It is very possible that the heat of the furnace feels as if it will melt you entirely, but the Lord only allows it to reach the exact temperature needed to refine you and burn away the impurities. The trial is less than a just punishment. It is a means of correction and spiritual education without which it is impossible for us to reach any degree of greatness in the kingdom of God. Now, if the trial produces endurance, the trial also drives us to our knees in prayer. And this is where wisdom enters the picture. James says: if any of you lacks wisdom, let him ask of God, who gives to all generously and without reproach. The Christian never needs wisdom more than when they are in the middle of a trial, because the outcome depends on whether you bear it correctly, according to the will of God and until the time appointed by the Father. We need wisdom so that we choose the true path without turning to the right or to the left. We need wisdom so that we understand what God wants us to learn when He denies us something we desperately wanted. We need wisdom when He places a heavy burden on our shoulders that we did not ask for. But there is a condition: ask in faith, without doubting. The one who doubts is like a wave of the sea, thrown back and forth by the wind. James calls this person 'double minded,' a word that in the original language literally means 'two souled.' This person is unstable in everything, not just in prayer but in all of life. The heroism of faith, as one theologian beautifully wrote, manifests itself in two ways: it is both suffering and militant. It endures and it fights. And the one who endures to the end will receive the crown of life that the Lord has promised to those who love Him."}, {"t": "Provision and Sustenance: The Father of Lights (James 1:13-18)", "c": "After establishing the purpose of trials, James now addresses a dangerous lie that some were telling themselves: 'I am tempted by God.' Let no one say that, James responds, because God cannot be tempted by evil, and He Himself tempts no one. Each person is tempted when they are dragged away by their own desire and enticed. Then desire, when it has conceived, gives birth to sin, and sin when it is fully grown produces death. Notice the progression: desire, conception, birth, growth, death. Sin operates like a pregnancy. It starts invisible, grows in secret, and eventually produces something that cannot be hidden. James is telling us: do not blame God for your failures. The enemy is closer than you think. It lives inside your own heart. But then, in one of the most beautiful transitions in all of Scripture, James pivots from the darkness of temptation to the brilliance of divine generosity. 'Do not be deceived, my beloved brothers. Every good gift and every perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, with whom can be no variation nor turning shadow.' God is the source of everything good in your life. He is not subject to the laws of the market. He does not respond to any earthly government. He does not need to check the exchange rate or follow the trends of the moment. If an earthly investor takes care of his enterprise, will not the Father of lights take infinitely greater care of His children? The detail is this: the Lord is more interested in your sanctification and your spiritual growth than in your economic prosperity. That is the reality. And that is why James adds: 'Of His own will He gave birth to us by the word of truth, that we should be a kind of firstfruits of His creatures.' He called us to be firstfruits. That word implies position, recognition, and preservation. If you are His child, you can be certain that whatever happens, the Lord will take care of you. That does not mean you will never suffer, or feel pain, or experience moments of great need. God does not raise spoiled and entitled children. In the moments of hardship, disappointment, and suffering, He is often dealing with the unfinished business of our hearts, those things we have not yet talked about with Him, those areas we have not yet surrendered. The trial, the difficulty, the tribulation is often the workshop where the Lord is sculpting us, removing the excess material of sin, unbelief, and the habits that want to stop our spiritual growth."}, {"t": "Attitudes, Communication and Living the Word (James 1:19-27)", "c": "James now gives us three commands that, if we actually obeyed them, would transform every relationship in our lives: be swift to hear, slow to speak, and slow to anger. The order matters. First listen. Then speak. And let anger be the very last thing you reach for. The anger of man does not produce the righteousness of God. How many arguments could have been avoided if we had simply listened before we opened our mouths? How many friendships could have been saved if we had been slow to react instead of quick to explode? A wise man once said: 'Blessed is the man whose mouth is in his heart and whose heart is not in his mouth. The one is wisdom; the other is foolishness.' We should speak the Word more to our own hearts and avoid putting our hearts into our reckless speaking, because the heart of man is deceitful above all things. It will not be our zeal for the Word that illuminates the understanding of those who are deceived. It will not be our intellect or our power of persuasion that converts the heart. Only the power of the Spirit can save. But the way we express ourselves can determine whether people will listen to us at all. Then James introduces one of his most famous illustrations: the mirror. If anyone is a hearer of the word and not a doer, he is like a man who looks at his natural face in a mirror, sees the mess, and walks away without fixing anything. In the first century, mirrors were not made of glass but of polished metal. The image was real but imperfect. When you hear the Word of God, it shows you who you truly are and who you ought to be. But if you hear and do nothing, you remain exactly as you were, and the hearing served no purpose at all. The true internal hearing, as one scholar wrote, is always receiving again the word that has already been implanted within us as the seed of regeneration. What good would the preached word be unless it had hidden points of contact in the hearts and consciences of believers? The hearer who forgets corresponds exactly to the second type of soil in the parable of the Sower. Finally, James closes this chapter with a definition of true religion that is breathtaking in its simplicity: visit orphans and widows in their affliction, and keep yourself unstained by the world. That is it. Not buildings, not programs, not impressive liturgies. Visit the people nobody visits. Help the people nobody helps. And guard your heart from the contamination of a world that wants to reshape you in its image. This is the religion that is pure and undefiled before God the Father."}, {"t": "A Final Word", "c": "Brothers and sisters, this first chapter of the Epistle of James is a treasury of practical wisdom anchored in the unchanging character of God. If we consider our faith, then inevitably we must recognize that it is an active faith, one that is dynamic, living, and in constant movement, responding and growing in our relationship with the Lord. If our faith grows in dependence on Him, it will only be through the trial and the tribulation. That same tribulation will exercise our patience, and in it we will find good soil to acquire and learn wisdom that is essential for the Christian life. That wisdom will give us discernment to understand that God is the Father of lights from whom comes every good gift and every perfect gift. He is our provision. He is our sustenance. And in Him there is no variation, no shadow of change. May the Lord preserve us in His faith, provide for us in His generosity, and teach us to live in silence and with gratitude the Christian life that He has called us to live."}]}, "2": {"title": "Love and Works in the Faith", "sections": [{"t": "Introduction", "c": "In his autobiography, Mahatma Gandhi wrote that during his student days he read the Gospels seriously and considered becoming a Christian. He believed that in Jesus he could find the solution to the caste system that divided the people of India. One Sunday he decided to attend a church service and speak with the minister about converting. But when he entered the sanctuary, the usher refused to give him a seat and suggested he go worship with his own people. Gandhi left that church and never returned. 'If Christians also have differences of caste,' he said, 'I might as well remain a Hindu.' Whether this story is entirely accurate in every detail, the principle it illustrates is devastating. The world is watching how we treat people, and when our practice contradicts our profession, we become the greatest obstacle to the very Gospel we claim to believe. James understood this danger. In this second chapter, he attacks two of the most destructive diseases that can infect a local church: the sin of showing favoritism to the wealthy while despising the poor, and the deadly illusion of a faith that talks but never acts. He does so with the intensity of a man who has no time for religious games and no patience for comfortable Christianity."}, {"t": "The Faith that Loves Without Partiality (James 2:1-13)", "c": "James opens this chapter with a command that cuts straight to the bone: do not hold the faith of our glorious Lord Jesus Christ with partiality. The grammar here is important. He is not making a suggestion. He is identifying something that was already happening in these churches and telling them to stop. The hypothetical scenario he paints is vivid. A man walks into the assembly wearing a gold ring and fine clothing, and immediately the ushers give him the best seat. Then a poor man comes in with dirty clothes, and they tell him to stand over there, or sit on the floor by my footstool. Have you not made distinctions among yourselves, James asks, and become judges with evil thoughts? In the ancient Jewish tradition, when an accused person came before a judge, it was customary according to the law that they should not lift their face before the judge. This way, if the accused happened to be a relative of the judge, or someone wealthy and influential, or a close friend, the judge would not be able to recognize them and show favoritism. James is applying that same principle to the church: do not lift the face of anyone because of their appearance, their wealth, or their social status. As Paul teaches in Galatians: there is neither Jew nor Greek, neither slave nor free, neither male nor female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus. Everything that men have built to divide and segregate one another, God has torn down in Christ. As one preacher once said, the ground is level at the foot of the cross. Then James delivers a devastating blow: did not God choose the poor of this world to be rich in faith and heirs of the kingdom? The poor believe. The Gospel is preached to them. And yet in many churches today, the pattern of favoritism continues under different names. Those who give the largest offerings get the best treatment. Those who have influence get special access. Those who cannot contribute financially are quietly pushed to the margins. James reminds us that showing partiality is not just poor etiquette. It is sin. And the royal law of Scripture commands us to love our neighbor as ourselves. If you keep the whole law but stumble in this one point, you are guilty of all of it. But then James offers one of the most beautiful statements in all of Scripture: mercy triumphs over judgment. If God dealt with us strictly by the rules, none of us would survive. But mercy steps in, looks at what we deserve, and chooses to give us something infinitely better. We are called to extend that same mercy to every person who walks through our doors."}, {"t": "The Faith that Works Without Excuses (James 2:14-20)", "c": "Now James enters the passage that has generated more theological debate than perhaps any other in the New Testament: the relationship between faith and works. What good is it, he asks, if someone says he has faith but has no works? Can that faith save him? Before we go any further, let us be clear about something that many people misunderstand. James and Paul are not contradicting each other. They are teaching two sides of the same coin. They are showing two wings of the same bird. They speak to two different groups with two different problems using the same words. Paul was dealing with people who said that works of the law must be added to faith in order to earn God's favor. Paul answered that error by declaring that salvation is by faith alone, apart from works of the law. But Paul also taught that saving faith is not dead; it is alive and works through love. James, on the other hand, was dealing with people who said that since they had faith, they did not need to demonstrate love through a life of obedience. James answered that error by teaching that faith which produces no evidence of life is not real faith at all. Both James and Paul teach that salvation is by faith alone, and both teach that genuine faith is never alone; it always manifests itself through acts of love that express the believer's gratitude to God. James then paints another hypothetical scenario to drive his point home. A brother or sister comes to you without clothing and without food. And you say to them: 'Go in peace, be warm and be filled,' but you give them nothing they actually need. What good is that? If your theology consists of sending people away with pious words while your wallet is full and your pantry is stocked, then examine your profession of faith carefully. On the day of judgment, the Lord will not ask who made the prayer of faith, or who was under the coverage of the most anointed apostle, or who had the most impressive theological degrees. He will ask: I was hungry, and did you feed me? I was thirsty, and did you give me water? I was a stranger, and did you welcome me? I was sick, and did you visit me? Even the demons believe that God is one, and they tremble. They have a theology far more complete than ours. They know God intimately. And yet in all their knowledge they have rejected Him, turned their backs on Him, and been condemned for their rebellion."}, {"t": "The Faith that is Proven: Abraham and Rahab (James 2:21-26)", "c": "What James does next is very radical, very bold, and deeply intentional, especially considering his audience. He takes two characters from the Old Testament and places them side by side as examples of living faith: Abraham and Rahab. Think about the contrast. Abraham is the father of the faith, the patriarch, the man who believed God and went out in obedience. God raised from him a nation from which the Messiah would come. He was deeply respected in Jewish tradition, honored above almost all others. And Rahab? A prostitute. A Canaanite woman. A foreigner with no standing, no reputation, and no merit. And yet both of them appear in the genealogy of the Lord Jesus Christ. What does this teach us? First, that God was not partial in giving the gift of faith. He chose by grace both one and the other. Second, both participated in the expansion of God's plan. Third, both proved their faith through actions and deeds. Abraham believed the promise and waited in faith, and then his faith was manifested when he climbed the mountain to offer his son Isaac. He had to have already killed Isaac in his heart before God stopped his hand. Rahab believed the promise that she would be adopted into the family of Israel regardless of her profession, her ethnicity, and her past, and her faith was proven when she risked her life and the life of her family to hide the spies at Jericho. James closes this argument with an illustration that leaves no room for misunderstanding: as the body without the spirit is dead, so faith without works is dead. A body lying on a table that does not breathe, does not move, does not respond to anything, that body is not sleeping. It is dead. In the exact same way, a faith that confesses Christ on Sunday but lives as if He does not exist from Monday to Saturday is not a weak faith. It is a dead faith. When we have truly come to know Jesus in a living, personal relationship and not merely in the intellect, our entire life, our thoughts, and our actions must change. We will not become perfect. We will not stop sinning entirely. But evidently we will not be the same persons we were before. Our life will no longer revolve around the world but around the Lord."}, {"t": "A Final Word", "c": "Brothers and sisters, this chapter confronts us with two of the most uncomfortable questions we can face. The first is: do I treat people differently based on what they can do for me? And the second is: does my daily life provide any visible evidence that my faith is real? James is not trying to make us feel guilty. He is trying to wake us up. The faith that loves without partiality and the faith that works without excuses are not two different kinds of faith. They are the same living faith expressed in two directions: toward the people around us and toward the God who saved us. May the Lord give us the grace to examine our hearts honestly, to repent where we have failed, and to live the kind of faith that Abraham and Rahab demonstrated, a faith that does not merely confess with the mouth but confirms with the hands, the feet, and the open doors of our lives."}]}, "3": {"title": "The Tongue: Teachers, Fire and Wisdom", "sections": [{"t": "Introduction", "c": "There is an old story about a woman who once approached one of the Puritan ministers in London and told him that the scarves he wore with his pulpit suit were too long and that they bothered her enormously. She asked his permission to shorten them. Graciously, he consented, and the woman, who had come prepared with scissors, cut the scarves to her liking and returned the pieces to the minister. When he received them, he thanked her and said: 'Now, my good woman, there is something on you that is too long and that has bothered me greatly, and since one good turn deserves another, I would like permission to shorten it.' 'Certainly,' said the woman, 'you have my permission, and here are the scissors.' To which the minister replied: 'Very well, madam, please stick out your tongue.' It is a humorous story, but it carries a truth that is anything but funny. The tongue is the most powerful and the most dangerous member of the human body. Through the analysis of the tongue, a doctor can diagnose the diseases of the body, a philosopher can diagnose the diseases of the mind, and the Christian can diagnose the diseases of the soul. James dedicates this entire chapter to two closely related subjects: the enormous responsibility of those who teach the Word of God, and the terrifying power of the tongue that every human being carries in their mouth. These are not separate topics. They are deeply connected, because the teacher is the person whose tongue carries the greatest weight and the greatest potential for both healing and destruction."}, {"t": "The Responsibility of Teachers and the Power of Words (James 3:1-6)", "c": "James opens with a warning that should make every pastor, elder, and Sunday school teacher pause and reflect: let not many of you become teachers, my brothers, knowing that we will receive a stricter judgment. The word he uses for 'become' in the original language does not simply mean 'to be.' It carries the idea of constituting yourself, of setting yourself up in a position. James is not discouraging the gift of teaching. He is warning against the rush to occupy a position of authority without understanding the weight of responsibility that comes with it. In the Jewish tradition, a rabbi was treated with the highest respect. The obligations toward a rabbi were said to exceed even the obligations toward a father, because parents give you existence in this world, but a rabbi gives you existence in the world to come. It was tremendously easy for a rabbi to become the kind of person Jesus described: a spiritual tyrant, a trafficker in piety, someone in love with distinctions and public respect. The same danger exists today. There are teachers who twist the doctrine of grace to suit their own agendas. There are pastors whose private lives contradict every word they preach from the pulpit. There are leaders who were placed in authority before they were spiritually ready, and the result is always the same: false doctrines entering the church, problems of conduct, either excessive or absent discipline, divisions over authority, and congregations that slowly transform into something that looks more like a cult than a family of believers. Then James moves to the tongue itself, and his illustrations are unforgettable. A small bit controls the mouth of a powerful horse and directs the entire animal. A small rudder steers a massive ship through fierce winds. In the same way, the tongue is a small member but it boasts of great things. And then the image becomes terrifying: see how a small fire can spread to a large forest. The tongue is a fire. It is a world of iniquity set among our members, defiling the whole body and setting the entire course of life on fire, and it is itself set on fire by the very pit of hell. This is the only place outside of the words of Jesus where this particular word for hell appears in the New Testament. James is telling us that the destructive power of reckless speech has a diabolical origin. When we give free rein to our tongues, we are not merely being careless. We are allowing an instrument of hell to operate through us."}, {"t": "The Untamable Evil and the Dignity of Every Person (James 3:7-12)", "c": "James now makes a statement that, at first glance, seems to offer no hope at all: every kind of animal, bird, reptile, and sea creature has been tamed by human beings, but no human being can tame the tongue. It is a restless evil, full of deadly poison. With it we bless our God and Father, and with it we curse people who are made in the image of God. Out of the same mouth come blessing and cursing. My brothers, these things ought not to be so. The sharp and cutting tongue is the only tool that becomes sharper the more it is used. And many of us have reason to repent more of the things we have said than of the things we kept to ourselves. But if no one can tame the tongue, does that mean we are hopeless? Not at all. Just as the horse needs the rider and the ship needs the pilot, our tongue needs the Lord to control it. A tongue that is under the governance of the Holy Spirit is evidence that the one directing and controlling is God Himself, not our flesh. There is also a profound point about human dignity embedded in this passage. James says we curse people who are made in the image of God. God made every human being in His image and likeness. He never did this with any angel. Christ Jesus did not die for angels. He died for people, for the ones chosen by God for salvation, for His people. Should this not tell us something about the value and respect we owe to every person? Each human being, regardless of whether they deserve our kindness or not, regardless of whether they are Christian or not, was made in the image of God. That image has been damaged and scarred by sin, but it is still there. That is the argument James is making: you are not better than anyone else when you insult, mistreat, or speak all kinds of evil against another person. Then James uses nature to drive the point home. Does a spring pour out fresh water and bitter water from the same opening? Can a fig tree produce olives, or a vine produce figs? Of course not. And in the same way, no spring should produce both salt water and fresh water. The hypocrisy of using the same mouth to sing hymns to God on Sunday and to curse our neighbor on Monday reveals that something at the very root of our lives has not been truly surrendered to the Lord."}, {"t": "Two Kinds of Wisdom: From Below and From Above (James 3:13-18)", "c": "James closes this chapter by painting a vivid contrast between two kinds of wisdom. The first is earthly, unspiritual, and demonic. Where there is bitter jealousy and selfish ambition, there is disorder and every kind of evil practice. This is the wisdom that builds platforms instead of people, that turns congregations into franchises, and that measures success by numbers, fame, and influence rather than by faithfulness to the Word. It is very sad to observe how many pastors look down on other pastors because of the university where they studied, or the size of the church they lead, or the liturgical tradition they follow, or how famous they are. There are pastors who never returned to a fellowship of ministers because of the shallowness, arrogance, and condescension they encountered. Pastors of large congregations tend to treat pastors of small churches differently. If the highest standard for many leaders is not the Bible itself, then anything can take its place: the fame of this one, the anointing of that one, the reputation of another, the number of members, the size of the buildings, the trends of the moment. But the wisdom that comes from above is first pure, then peaceable, gentle, reasonable, full of mercy and good fruits, without partiality and without hypocrisy. Notice that purity comes first. Before you worry about being peaceful or gentle, make sure that your heart is clean before God. And then the fruit of righteousness is sown in peace by those who make peace. A true biblical teacher and pastor is one who is called by the Lord, whose calling is confirmed by the sheep who follow. A true pastor smells like sheep, because he has been among them. A true pastor feeds the flock, not counts the flock, because what matters is not how many are present but how well they are being nourished. A true pastor protects the sheep from wolves and disciplines the sheep who wander. A true pastor has two voices: one for calling the sheep, and another for scaring away the wolves. And a true pastor uses the shepherd's staff, not a pillow. The staff is used to pull the wandering sheep back by the neck, and to give a little tap on the leg to the one that is jumping around too much. These are the marks of the biblical shepherd."}, {"t": "A Final Word", "c": "Brothers and sisters, this chapter confronts every one of us. Whether you teach or not, you carry a tongue in your mouth, and that tongue has the power to build up or to tear down, to heal or to wound, to bless or to curse. James is not telling us to stop talking. He is telling us to surrender our speech to the Lord, to let the Holy Spirit be the pilot of the ship and the rider of the horse. When the urge to speak is strongest, when the temptation to lash out is most intense, when we feel that we simply cannot hold it in any longer, that is precisely the moment when we must ask the Lord for patience and wisdom to remain silent. It is not about being quiet when it is convenient. It is about exercising self-control when every part of our flesh is screaming to speak. May the Lord make our tongues instruments of peace, of truth, and of the kind of wisdom that comes from above, the wisdom that is pure, peaceable, gentle, full of mercy, and without hypocrisy."}]}, "4": {"title": "The World, Humility and the Will of God", "sections": [{"t": "Introduction", "c": "When the apostle Paul wrote to the Christians in Philippi, he knew how important it was for them to understand the concept of living as citizens of one place while physically residing in another. Philippi was a Roman colony, a model city that replicated Roman customs, Roman architecture, Roman clothing, and the Latin language, even though it was nearly a thousand miles from Rome. If you walked into the city, you would feel as if you had entered an Italian suburb of the capital itself. So when Paul told those believers, 'Our citizenship is in heaven,' they understood exactly what he meant. But there is an important difference between the Christian calling and the human tendency to make ourselves at home in foreign territory. The difference is that no matter how well we adapt, no matter how creative our efforts, Christians must never forget that this world is not our home. There is a sense of displacement that must remain at the core of all our experiences. Adaptation may be second nature, but it can also be the death of our first nature, the nature created in the image of God and then recreated by His grace in Christ. This fourth chapter of James confronts us with the stark reality of that tension. Where do wars and conflicts come from? From our own pleasures that wage war inside us. What happens when we try to be friends with both God and the world? We become enemies of God. And what is the only path forward? Humility, submission, and an honest recognition that our life is a vapor that appears for a little while and then vanishes."}, {"t": "The War Within and the Friendship that Kills (James 4:1-6)", "c": "James opens this chapter with a question that pierces straight to the root of human conflict: where do wars and fights among you come from? Do they not come from your pleasures that war in your members? Every day, in every moment, we fight an internal battle between the Spirit and the flesh that rebels. It is a constant struggle to die to ourselves and live for Christ. Success, fame, and riches are always around the corner, and all it takes is for us to shift our gaze and change our direction. But what happens when the things we do not have become the center of our lives instead of Christ? What are we willing to do for comfort, for luxury, for influence and power? You covet and do not have. You murder and are consumed with envy but cannot obtain. You fight and make war. And yet you do not have, because you do not ask. And when you do ask, you do not receive, because you ask with wrong motives, so that you may spend it on your pleasures. James is describing prayers that are aimed at the wrong target. We must learn to value patience, the joy of salvation, and the countless blessings of the Christian life that have nothing to do with material possessions. Can we ask in moments of need, not only for material provision but also for the comfort to endure the circumstance? Can we ask for peace to continue day after day without losing hope? Can we ask for joy when our season is one of sadness and affliction? Can we ask for grace when we are being stung by sin and our own wickedness? A survivor of the Nazi concentration camps, who lost his entire family in the Second World War, once said: 'They can take almost everything from a man, but they cannot take away what he chooses to do with the circumstances he faces.' Then James delivers one of the most sobering warnings in all of Scripture: you adulterers and adulteresses, do you not know that friendship with the world is hostility toward God? Whoever wants to be a friend of the world makes himself an enemy of God. As Spurgeon once said: 'If I had a brother who had been murdered, what would you think of me if I daily kept company with the assassin who drove the dagger into my brother's heart? Sin murdered Christ; will you be a friend to it?' But God gives more grace. He resists the proud, but He gives grace to the humble. The proud get opposition. The humble get power."}, {"t": "Humility, Grace and Drawing Near to God (James 4:7-10)", "c": "James now gives us a series of commands that read like marching orders for the soldier of Christ. Submit to God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you. Draw near to God, and He will draw near to you. Cleanse your hands, you sinners. Purify your hearts, you double minded. The way we resist the devil is not through spiritual warfare rituals, or by rebuking him at every corner, or by performing mystical ceremonies and attaching Christian symbols to everything we own. The way we resist the devil is this: in the evil day, in the crucial moment of trial and affliction, we fall on our faces and worship the Lord. We embrace the will of God, exalting and glorifying His name because He is worthy, regardless of what is happening around us, even if it costs us our lives. Remember the three young men in Babylon: 'Our God whom we serve is able to deliver us from the burning fiery furnace. But even if He does not, let it be known to you, O king, that we will not serve your gods or worship the golden image.' And remember Job, who after losing everything he had, stood up, tore his robe, shaved his head, and fell to the ground in worship, saying: 'The Lord gave, and the Lord has taken away. Blessed be the name of the Lord.' The devil is a proud and arrogant being. He hates seeing believers take the posture of Job. That is what resistance looks like: not shouting at the darkness, but worshiping in the middle of it. According to the context of what James has been teaching, how do we draw near to God and purify our hearts? By combating our flesh in order to live for the glory of God. By abandoning the craving for the comfortable and pleasurable life that the world offers. By using our hands to serve the church of Christ and not merely our own interests. Our hearts are purified when we meditate on the virtue of humility, when we can humble ourselves without complaining and give thanks for the little or the much that we have. Lament, mourn, and weep, James says. Our pain, our tears, and our lament are a pleasing aroma before the Lord when we bring them to Him in surrender. He does not forbid us from crying. He simply asks that we do it in His presence, trusting Him and waiting on Him for our rescue and consolation."}, {"t": "The Danger of Judging and the Brevity of Life (James 4:11-17)", "c": "James now addresses two final issues that reveal the arrogance of the human heart: speaking evil against one another and making plans as if we were in control of tomorrow. Do not speak against one another, brothers. He who speaks against a brother and judges his brother speaks against the law and judges the law. But if you judge the law, you are not a doer of the law but a judge. There is only one Lawgiver and Judge, the one who is able to save and to destroy. But who are you to judge another? There is an old story about Charles Spurgeon and Joseph Parker, who both had churches in London in the nineteenth century. Parker once commented on the condition of children admitted to Spurgeon's orphanage, and it was reported to Spurgeon that Parker had criticized the orphanage itself. Spurgeon attacked Parker from the pulpit the following Sunday. The newspapers printed the story and it became the talk of the town. People flocked to Parker's church to hear his response. Instead of retaliating, Parker said: 'I understand Dr. Spurgeon is not in his pulpit today, and this is the Sunday they take an offering for the orphanage. I suggest we take a love offering here instead.' The crowd was delighted. The ushers had to empty the collection plates three times. Later that week, Spurgeon knocked on Parker's door. 'You have practiced grace on me,' he said. 'You have given me not what I deserved but what I needed.' That is the spirit James is calling for. Criticism based on personal grudges, envy, or selfish interests is not discernment. It is sin. Then James turns to the brevity of life. Come now, you who say, 'Today or tomorrow we will go into this city and spend a year there and trade and make a profit.' Yet you do not know what your life will be like tomorrow. You are a vapor that appears for a little time and then vanishes. Instead, you ought to say, 'If the Lord wills, we will live and do this or that.' The doctrine of Divine Providence affirms that God is in absolute control of all things. This doctrine stands in direct opposition to the idea that the universe is governed by chance. The believer is not an arrogant person who rebels against the purposes of God. And then the chapter closes with a statement that haunts every comfortable Christian: to the one who knows the right thing to do and does not do it, to him it is sin."}, {"t": "A Final Word", "c": "Brothers and sisters, this chapter calls us to a radical honesty about our lives. Are we fighting wars that come from our own selfish desires? Are we trying to maintain a friendship with the world while claiming to love God? Are we making plans for tomorrow as if we were the ones in control? James is not condemning ambition or planning. He is condemning the arrogance that forgets God in the process. May we learn to hold our plans with open hands, to humble ourselves before the Lord so that He may lift us up in His timing, and to live every day with the sober awareness that our life is a vapor, and that every moment is an opportunity to glorify the one who gave it to us."}]}, "5": {"title": "Resources, Attitude and Will in Christ", "sections": [{"t": "Introduction", "c": "There is a striking image that captures the state of the world without Christ. The motors of a clock, separated from their pendulum, were left sitting in a living room. The seconds ticked away frantically. Without the pendulum, the entire intricate mechanism rattled in a blind rush, going nowhere. That is a picture of the world today. God created all things to move in proper balance, but humanity has rejected the Lord Jesus Christ, who is the Providence of God. People speak of Providence as if it were a force, but Scripture says it is a Person: Christ, who sustains all things by the word of His power. Nothing will move to perfection until He returns. This fifth and final chapter of James brings together the great themes of the letter in a powerful crescendo. It addresses the wealthy who have oppressed their workers and hoarded their riches. It calls believers to patient endurance as they wait for the coming of the Lord. And it closes with some of the most practical instructions on prayer, confession, and the restoration of the wanderer that we find anywhere in the New Testament. James begins with thunder and ends with tenderness, and the thread that holds it all together is the unshakable reality that the Judge is standing at the door."}, {"t": "A Warning to the Oppressors and the Stewardship of Resources (James 5:1-6)", "c": "James opens this chapter with words that should make every comfortable person sit up and pay attention: come now, you rich, weep and howl for the miseries that are coming upon you. Your riches are corrupted. Your garments are moth eaten. Your gold and silver are corroded, and their corrosion will be a testimony against you and will eat your flesh like fire. You have stored up treasure in the last days. It is important to understand that James is not condemning wealth itself. The Bible recognizes both the pious poor and the pious rich. The widow of Zarephath was poor but faithful. Abraham, David, and Solomon were wealthy but devoted to God. Joseph of Arimathea and Nicodemus were rich men who served the Lord. What James condemns is not having wealth but abusing it, specifically in three terrible sins: the injustice of withholding wages from laborers, the hoarding of possessions that will testify against their owners on the day of judgment, and the extravagant living that fattens the heart while others go hungry. The word James uses for 'Lord' when he says 'the Lord of Armies' is remarkable. In the original language, this title speaks of God as the commander of the heavenly hosts, the one who has an army at His disposal that no earthly power can resist. This is the only time this title appears in the New Testament outside of a direct Old Testament quotation. James is pulling out the heaviest artillery to make his point: the cries of the cheated workers have reached the ears of the God who commands the armies of heaven. The material possessions of the world that are not used for the glory of God become nothing more than evidence of condemnation for those who hoard them. The question is not whether you are rich or poor, but what your resources are doing for the kingdom. Are you a steward who manages what belongs to God, or a proprietor who acts as if it all belongs to you?"}, {"t": "The Patient Farmer and the Coming of the Lord (James 5:7-12)", "c": "After the thunder comes the tenderness. James now turns to the believers and says: be patient, therefore, brothers, until the coming of the Lord. And he gives us one of the most beautiful illustrations in the entire letter: the farmer who waits for the precious fruit of the earth, being patient over it until it receives the early and late rain. The farmer plants the seed and then waits. He does not dig up the seed every morning to see if it has sprouted. He trusts the process. He trusts the rain. He trusts the seasons. In the same way, we are called to establish our hearts, because the coming of the Lord is near. One scholar has estimated that there are 1,845 references to the second coming of Christ in the Old Testament, and 318 references in the 260 chapters of the New Testament, roughly one in every thirty verses. For every prophecy about the first coming of Christ, there are eight that point to His second coming. This is not a minor doctrine. It is one of the central pillars of the Christian hope. Then James addresses a problem that had developed among the suffering believers: they had begun to grumble and complain against one another. The oppression from the rich had created bitterness, and that bitterness had turned inward. James corrects them: do not grumble against one another, brothers, so that you may not be judged. The Judge is standing at the door. He hears everything. And we must not invade the prerogative of the one who alone has the right to render the final verdict. James points them to the prophets who spoke in the name of the Lord as examples of suffering and patience. He points them to Job, whose story demonstrates that God always has a purpose and a wonderful outcome in mind, even when we cannot see it. The Lord is full of compassion and mercy. Then James gives a final instruction about integrity in communication: do not swear, neither by heaven nor by earth nor by any other oath. Let your yes be yes and your no be no. The background is clear. There were people who could not keep their word. In the ancient world, as in ours, a person's reliability was measured by whether they did what they said they would do. James is saying: be the kind of person whose simple word is as binding as any oath. A true Christian community is one where everyone maintains their word as sacred, and where the mutual trust is so deep that oaths become unnecessary."}, {"t": "Prayer, Confession and Restoring the Wanderer (James 5:13-20)", "c": "James closes his letter with instructions so practical that they could serve as a handbook for any local church. Is anyone among you suffering? Let him pray. Is anyone cheerful? Let him sing praises. These are not suggestions. They are imperatives. The Christian life should be marked by a balanced and steady response to both good days and bad days, as prescribed here. In contrast with the complaints, criticisms, denunciations, and curses that James has been addressing throughout the letter, the believer's response to affliction should be prayer, and the response to joy should be praise. Is anyone sick? Let him call for the elders of the church, and let them pray over him, anointing him with oil in the name of the Lord. And the prayer of faith will save the one who is sick, and the Lord will raise him up. It is important to understand two dangerous extremes: the first says that sickness has no relationship to sin whatsoever, and the second says that sickness is always a direct product of sin. The truth is somewhere in the middle. James connects the healing of the body with the confession of sin and the prayer of the community. The oil served both as a medicinal remedy, since oil was commonly used for healing in the ancient world, and as a symbol of the care and attention of the church. The willingness of the sick person to call for the elders, to confess their condition of weakness, to ask for help, is itself an act of humility and surrender. Then James points us to Elijah, a man with a nature just like ours, who prayed earnestly that it would not rain, and it did not rain for three years and six months. And he prayed again, and the sky gave rain, and the earth produced its fruit. Elijah was not a superhero. He was a man who struggled with fear, with depression, with the desire to give up. After his greatest victory on Mount Carmel, he ran away from Jezebel and sat under a tree asking God to take his life. And yet this same fragile, imperfect man moved heaven and earth through prayer. If Elijah can do it, so can you. Finally, James closes with a word about restoring the one who has wandered from the truth. If anyone among you wanders from the truth and someone turns him back, let him know that he who turns a sinner from the error of his way will save a soul from death and will cover a multitude of sins. The letter that began with trials ends with restoration. The letter that opened with testing closes with rescue. This is the heart of God: not to leave His sheep wandering in the darkness, but to send someone after them to bring them home."}, {"t": "A Final Word", "c": "Brothers and sisters, the Epistle of James began with a call to count it all joy in the face of trials, and it ends with a call to pray, to confess, and to go after the one who has lost their way. James started his letter with the Sermon on the Mount, saying 'blessed is the one who endures temptation,' and he closes it with the same spirit, saying 'we count as blessed those who have persevered.' Between those two bookends lies a letter that refuses to let us separate our Sunday faith from our Monday life. May the Lord give us faith that endures, tongues that heal, wisdom that comes from above, hearts that are humble before Him, and the courage to live every day as the vapor that it is, filled with purpose, with gratitude, and with the unshakable hope that the Judge who stands at the door is also our Redeemer, the one who has already declared us not guilty through the precious blood of Christ."}]}};
